comment_body:
instead of putting the list directly in the test and looping through it, junit offers something called a [ParamaterizedTest](https://www.baeldung.com/parameterized-tests-junit-5). we use it by creating a "supplier" method, populating it with x values, and then the test will x times with each individual value. 

here's a general structure for how it may look:

```
@ParameterizedTest
@MethodSource("exceptionSupplier")
public void sendRequestThrowsTimeoutException(Exception exceptionType) {
// test
}

private static Stream<Arguments> exceptionSupplier() {
        return Stream.of(Arguments.of(TimeoutException.class),
            Arguments.of(RuntimeException.class),
            Arguments.of(ExecutionException.class),
            Arguments.of(InterruptedException.class)
            );
}
```

here i made an external supplier method because i personally think it looks cleaner, but you can also use `ValueSource` like in the doc I linked! 

if you want to see more examples of `ParameterizedTest`'s, they're all over our test files.

we can avoid using a try catch here by using another test convention, `assertThrows`. we should use this instead of a try catch because we are testing something that should always throw. we can then assign assertThrows to the runtime exception we are trying to catch, and call assertNotNull and assertInstanceOf on that. 

```
RuntimeException e = assertThrows(RuntimeException.class,
            () -> StorageImplUtils.sendRequest(operation, Duration.ofSeconds(120), BlobStorageException.class));
        assertNotNull(e.getCause());
        assertInstanceOf(exceptionType, e.getCause());

```

because parameter suppliers support multiple arguments, we can combine all this logic into it. instead of reflection-based construction (generateSupplier), we can supply callable instances directly. for the supplier method, we can follow the general structure of:

(Callable object that throws an exception type, expected cause)

Here's the new test and supplier, courtesy of copilot: (i verified it but you should too)

```
public class StorageImplUtilsTests {

    @ParameterizedTest
    @MethodSource("exceptionCallables")
    void sendRequestWrapsNonMatchingExceptions(Callable<?> operation, Class<? extends Exception> expectedCauseType) {
        RuntimeException e = assertThrows(RuntimeException.class,
            () -> StorageImplUtils.sendRequest(operation, Duration.ofSeconds(120), HttpResponseException.class));

        assertNotNull(e.getCause());
        assertInstanceOf(expectedCauseType, e.getCause());
    }

    private static Stream<Arguments> exceptionCallables() {
        return Stream.of(
            // Future completes exceptionally with TimeoutException as cause -> wrapped RuntimeException(cause)
            Arguments.of((Callable<Object>) () -> {
                throw new TimeoutException();
            }, TimeoutException.class),
            // Direct RuntimeException cause should be rethrown by sendRequest (no additional wrapping of cause)
            Arguments.of((Callable<Object>) () -> {
                throw new RuntimeException("rt");
            }, RuntimeException.class),
            // ExecutionException cause path -> RuntimeException(causeInsideExecutionException)
            Arguments.of((Callable<Object>) () -> {
                throw new ExecutionException("exec", new RuntimeException("inner"));
            }, ExecutionException.class),
            // Checked InterruptedException -> wrapped
            Arguments.of((Callable<Object>) () -> {
                throw new InterruptedException("int");
            }, InterruptedException.class));
    }
```

The JSON serialization order has changed - domainGuid is now written before netBiosDomainName and forestName, whereas it was previously written after them. This reordering could potentially break clients that depend on a specific field order in the JSON output.
```suggestion
